</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,289,964]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Drake" authorityYear="1948" box="[199,319,867,892]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Xynotingis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,319,867,892]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Xynotingis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fieber" authorityYear="1844" box="[451,610,866,892]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Physatocheila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[451,610,866,892]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Physatocheila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in general appearance but can be easily distinguished by the following characters: body rotund; head longer than its maximum width across compound eyes; and antennal segments I separated from each other at their bases.
</paragraph>
